item.title: My new set up!
item.dc:creator: @Ruby_Forums_Coder Ruby
item.description:
@Ruby_Forums_Coder wrote:

[quote=“wildskiller, post:27, topic:550248”][quote author=Ruby link=topic=669160.msg4475940#msg4475940 date=1425928538]

Overclocking seems to be simple to a lot of people. Really, it’s just changing the clock multiplier and voltage to give it more power. Intel Extreme Tuning Utility will help with a lot of that if you’re not sure you can handle the bios. The newer i3s, i5s, and i7s are already unlocked for you, so it should be easy with that tool. Also, I would go with water cooling for your CPU if you ever want to overclock. It’s not ENTIRELY needed, but it can do a lot better than most air-fanned CPUs and keeps the heat lower.

Overclocking really isn’t necessary if you have a new intel i3-5-7 because every core on them bad boys pack power and graphics. If your graphics card ever fails, then their onboard graphics can take over until you can get a new one. It’s not the best but you sure in hell can play Skyrim on medium-high with it.

Already got the i5-4690 non K so i can’t overclock now , or at-least not easily.

When i tried to OC my PC shutdown suddenly and when booted offered to return BIOS settings to default, which obviously meant i fudged something, so it seemed to risky to ruin the whole PC if anything happens by any chance. So no risks taken…

Overclocking may be simple, but it takes time. I believe the world record overclock took days using some liquid nitrogen, which I think is dry ice. So, if you keep failing your overclocking, then keep trying and expect the worst.

Liquid nitrogen isn’t anything like dry ice just fyi bruh
[/quote]
I know that dry ice and liquid nitrogen are very similar but don’t have the same elements inside. I heard some things on youtube about liquid nitrogen and dry ice in the same sentence and didn’t hear the entire conversation, so I just assumed they were the same thing.[/quote]
They aren’t very similar at all. Dry ice has a temperature of −78.5 °C, liquid nitrogen’s temperature is roughly −210 °C. Liquid nitrogen is hard to come by and incredibly unsafe to be using.

Read full topic
